regeneration of hepatocytes","Hyperplasia of Kupffer cells","Connective tissue deposition with scarring"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathology findings describe \u003Cstrong\u003Econnective tissue deposition with scarring\u003C/strong\u003E, which is one of the two main processes of tissue repair. When injured tissues are incapable of complete regeneration or when supporting structures are too severely damaged, repair occurs through the deposition of connective (fibrous) tissue, resulting in scar formation. In the liver, this process is often termed fibrosis and represents the laying down of collagen in response to chronic injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetaplasia of hepatocytes to fibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E - Hepatocytes do not transform into fibroblasts. Fibroblasts that produce collagen in liver fibrosis typically derive from hepatic stellate cells and portal fibroblasts.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrganisation of inflammatory exudate\u003C/strong\u003E - Organisation refers specifically to fibrosis developing in a tissue space previously occupied by an inflammatory exudate, which is not what is described in this liver biopsy.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete regeneration of hepatocytes\u003C/strong\u003E - While the liver has remarkable regenerative capacity through proliferation of surviving hepatocytes, the biopsy findings of extensive collagen deposition indicate that regeneration is incomplete and has been replaced by scarring.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperplasia of Kupffer cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Kupffer cells are liver macrophages that may increase in number during inflammation, but they are not responsible for the collagen deposition and architectural distortion described in the biopsy.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fibrous scar tissue provides structural stability but compromises normal liver function. This process of fibrosis is common in chronic liver diseases such as viral hepatitis, alcoholic liver disease, and non-alcoholic steatohepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tissue repair occurs through two main processes: regeneration (restoration of normal cells) and scarring (deposition of connective tissue).","Regeneration can occur through proliferation of differentiated cells (e.g., hepatocytes) or through tissue stem cells (e.g., in skin and intestinal epithelia).","Fibrosis refers to collagen deposition in organs like lungs, liver, and kidney as a consequence of chronic inflammation or extensive ischemic necrosis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 103"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77585"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20683"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77585"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T13:03:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T13:04:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13559"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94545"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":2,"createdAt":"202